Dorothy Boyd asks the flight attendant for a different kind of blanket for her son Ray, who appears to be allergic to the fabric. Ray gets sick and the flight attendant and Dorothy bond over helping him feel better. In first class, a  successful sports agent, Jerry Maguire, who works at Dorothy's company, remembers what it was like to ask his fiancé to marry him. Jerry, a cocky agent who has everything, explains the somewhat rocky proposal, but is still seemingly satisfied with his life.

Jerry Maguire is on the phone with his enthusiastic and ambitious client football player Rod Tidwell. Tidwell is angry at the lack of personal attention and he complains to Jerry. He explains that if he is going to stay with Jerry instead of signing with Jerry's rival, agent Bob Sugar, that Jerry will have to give more personal attention. Rod walks through his house shouting at Jerry, while the other lines on Jerry's phone slowly go out, leaving him only with Rod as a client.

After being fired from the sports agency where he worked as a successful agent, Jerry Maguire decides to leave and attempt to represent clients on his own. He gives a goodbye speech to the entire office where his boss, and his rival, Bob Sugar, just shake their heads. Jerry asks if anyone will come with him. His secretary Wendy refuses
however, financial analyst Dorothy Boyd agrees to go. Jerry and Dorothy leave and business resumes as usual in the office.
Jerry Maguire argues with Matt Cushman about the contract of his son, footballer Frank Cushman. Matt allowed Bob Sugar to take Frank's contract behind Jerry's back
Frank is the topic rookie pick for the NFL draft. Matt apologizes, but feels that Jerry is not capable of handling his son's contract in addition to the contract of Jerry's other client Rod Tidwell.

Jerry Maguire is drunk after losing Frank Cushman as his client. He goes to Dorothy Boyd's house and while she is changing in the other room, her son Ray comes out to talk to Jerry. Jerry giggles when Ray tells him a joke. Jerry's phone rings and Ray answers and talks to Jerry's client footballer Rod Tidwell. Rod does not know who has answered Jerry's phone. In other room, Dorothy and her sister Laurel are trying to decide what Dorothy should wear. Laurel tells her to be practical and Dorothy explains she is more mature than most women her age.

Jerry Maguire pleads to football player and client Rod Tidwell to sign to the football team even though he does not have a set contract. Rod argues and refuses. Jerry becomes frustrated and kicks at the wall. Jerry explains that the situation is difficult and he could use a little cooperation from Rod. Rod appreciates Jerry's dedication.

In the kitchen after spending an intimate night with her boss Jerry Maguire, Dorothy Boyd and her sister Laurel discuss the situation. Laurel doesn't want Dorothy to move too fast because she doesn't trust Jerry. Dorothy says she doesn't care if Jerry is at the bottom of the ladder because she loves him. Outside the kitchen, in the hallway, Jerry overhears the whole conversation. Dorothy's son Ray exposes Jerry to the two women who realize Jerry has heard the whole private conversation.

Jerry Maguire has gotten his client, football player Rod Tidwell, a car dealership commercial in the desert. Donning a turban and a football jersey, Rod sits on the camel and director Bill Dooler shouts at him. Seeing that Rod cannot handle the situation any longer and that the commercial was a bad idea from the start, Jerry pulls his Rod. As Rod and Jerry are leaving, Jerry asks if Rod knows anything about dating single mothers. Having been raises by a single mother Rod gives Jerry advice. Rods scolds Jerry for sleeping with Dorothy Boyd, as she is a single mother.

Sports agent Jerry Maguire waits outside the locker room for his client, football player Rod Tidwell. Rod has just played the game of his life and all the reporters and journalists and ready to interview him. As Rod exits the locker room the crowd clamors. Jerry smiles and tears up, excited for his friend and client. When he finally gets through the crowd Rod finds Jerry and they embrace.

Jerry Maguire interrupts the divorced women's group, that meets at his sister-in-law Laurel Boyd's home, to see his wife Dorothy and plead for her to take him. He explains his foolishness and that the company had a hugely successful night, but without her it wasn't the same. Jerry tells Dorothy he loves her and that she completes him
she tells him she's always been his.
